A pallet of UN1486 was placed on the 042 dock.  A forklift with another pallet was passing by the pallet of UN1486 and hit and tore a bag of the UN1486.  The bag spilled 10 pounds onto the dock next to the pallet.  The spill was recouped and placed into a recovery drum along with the damaged bag.  T he recovery drum will be held for OSandD
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: XPO Logistics terminal LHO experienced a release from a 5-gallon poly pail due to a puncture caused by improper dunnage. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3-gallons of product released to 3' x 4' area of the trailer floor & a 3' x 3' area of the asphalt lot below due to a puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged pail & cleanup debris were then placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

A pallet of UN1823 was damaged by shifting freight that was not properly secured.  A bag of the UN1823 was torn by the shifting freight. The spill was recouped and placed into a recovery drum with the damaged bag of UN1823.  It will be held for OSandD.

column168: On April 3, 2023, at 1015 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Ranger personnel in Alachua, Florida regarding the release of approximately 1 gallon of Eco-San (Hypochlorite solutions, UN1791 8, III) and approximately 8 gallons of Ultra-San (Hypochlorite solutions, UN1791 8, III).  The releases were reportedly due to leaks in the product containers.  The release was contained to the trailer floor.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The released products, spent absorbents and all other waste generated were containerized in (3) 55-gallon poly drums.  The waste drums were then transported off site for proper disposal.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Union Pacific Railroad yard personnel reported a tank car possibly leaking in the Anchorage Yard in Port Allen LA. Haz Mat Manager Tom Robinson was called for response. Mgr. Robinson discovered that the tank car was leaking the from the pressure relief device. The PRD had misaligned O-ring. The O-ring was properly putting back in place and the car stopped releasing vapors. The car was resealed and will be transferred at a later date because it was involved in a roll-over derailment on 3-29-2023.

XPO Logistics terminal LDA experienced a UN2920 1,1,3,3-Tetramethylguanidine release from a 55-gallon metal drum due to improper loading. ERTS dispatched contractor to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5-gallons of product was released to a 3’ x 3’ area of the trailer floor and a 3’ x 3’ area to the asphalt underneath the trailer. The drum was punctured by improper loading. Absorbents and neutralizers were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. All material was collected and containerized into a 55 and 95-gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed that approximately 1-tablespoon of the product was released to a 1’ x 1’ area of the cardboard packaging. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics Terminal UBY experienced a UN1760 "Clothesline Fresh Xtreme Laundry Sour" release from (2) 5-gallon poly pails due to improper loading. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed that 2 pails of Clothesline Fresh Xtreme Laundry Sour released approximately 2-ounces of to a 2’ x 2’ area of the trailer floor. The pails were crushed by the pallet falling over during transit due to improper securement. Absorbents and neutralizers were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. All released product was collected and containerized into a 15-gallon & 55-gallon poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

BJCA station called in with a package that felt cold to the touch, and they stated that this shipper has shipped Dry Ice in the past.  DG Admin instructed them to open the package and they found it did contain Dry Ice and what appeared to be blood samples.  Dg Admin instructed them to re-seal the package, and contact the shipper in order to get a release form to place a dry ice label on the package in order to send it on to destination.  The attached photos are all that were provided.  There are no indications on the outside package  that shows this package contains dry ice.

column168: Around 5pm central time I received a call from Toby Owens who works for Bozeman. Toby told me he was fueling up at the Loves at 335 LA-594, Monroe, LA, 71203 and was doing a walk around of set and noticed a pool of paint (UN1263, Paint, 3, PGIII) on ground and that it was still leaking from his rear pup (287281F). Toby notified central dispatch and they told him to contact Billy or myself. I contacted Hazmat One at 524pm and told them to make all the necessary phone calls and to take all waste with them. Toby mentioned it started to rain and Loves Truck Stop helped contain the spill from spreading more. Hazmat One arrived at Loves at 835pm to start cleaning spill. Hazmat One is renting a boom to unload trailer to clean up. They believe the leak is coming from a drum in nose of trailer. They projected a time of 600am to have spill cleaned up. Release was caused by a nail in the pallet the drums were loaded on. The nail during transit had punctured a hole in the bottom on one drum. Majority of material had leaked into the trailer

column168: On April 4, 2023 at 0005 hrs., TILX 110117 (Residue Last Contained, Hydrochloric Acid / UN 1780 / Class 8) was observed venting from the top during switching operations at CN Mays Yard.  The railcar was isolated and all departments notified.  The CN DGO responded.  Upon arrival and approaching the railcar, vapors were observed coming from the top.  Upon closer inspection, vapors were observed coming from a 3 bolt flange below the vapor line valve.  The bolts were checked and 2 of the 3 bolts were found to be less than tool tight.  1 of the 2 bolts was able to be tightened, the other bolt has to be changed due to deterioration from the acid.  Once the replacement bolts was installed and tightened, the leak was stopped.  The exterior of the railcar was decontaminated.  The railcar will be held at CN Mays yard for requalification.

column168: A tote of UN1866 has been damaged by an 086 forklift blade when the tote was being repositioned on the 086 dock.  The tote had a leak out the top of the tote when the tote is positioned on its side to move the puncture hole (1.5 inches) to the top side of the tote.  086 is attempted to fill the punc ture hole with shrinkwrap to stop the leak in the side of the tote. The plastic shrinkwrap that is being used to plug the puncture hole in the side of t he tote has slowed the spill from the puncture hole to a steady drip.  086 requested an immediate call for a HM cleanup team. ~~HazMat Spill Response Crew was dispatched to the location.~~NOTE: 086 had a tote from 04/06/2023, on the same shipment, that was leaking around the duct tape patch job done  by the spill team from 04/06/2023. The second leaking tote is dripping out the puncture hole from Friday, 4-7-23.  086 is requeste d animmediate call to a HM cleanup team for both leaking totes located on the 086 dock.  086 is using staydry to control the slow spillage coming from both totes.

column168: Poly 275 gal tote fell from the forks while attempting to be placed on top of another tote.  The poly tote burst and the contents released onto the warehouse floor.    The cause was from the bottom of top tote catching the bottom tote metal cage while repositioning.  The tote was caught and when top tote (that fell) was raised, the brought up the bottom tote.  Then the bottom tote fell and broke the bottom of top tote's pallet causing the tote to fall.  The waste profile B155-0631 shipping description Glycol Ether Universal Waste was contained in the warehouse.  Clean up was completed 4/6/2023.  The clean up resulted in a total of 8 drums (7 -55 gallon and 1- 85 gallon).
column169: Avoid double stacking poly totes with metal cages on top of each other.  confirm if tote is in good condition.

column168: There was a reported odor in the train yard by UP yard personnel at Settegast Yard in Houston TX. Haz Mat Manager Tom Robinson was called for a response. The car was discovered with the B-end liquid valve partially opened, and the plug was less than tool tight. column168: At the Toledo terminal the dockworker misjudged the position of their forks and punctured a 55-gallon plastic drum that was on a pallet being loaded in the trailer. The released material was neutralized and collected with absorbent material. The drum was placed in an overpack awaiting disposition from the shipper. We were unable to obtain identification markings on the drum due to the material being hazardous and not wanting to tamper with the material in the overpack.
column169: This incident may have been prevented had the employee been more aware of their fork position and surroundings. This employee was counselled and instructed per company policy. This incident may be used as an example in future dock training topics to show the importance of proper freight handling techniques.

column168: Allied International Emergency was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 25ft-by-25ft area of the concrete terminal floor and a 6ft-by-3ft area of the trailer floor and estimated that fifty (50) gallons of material was released from a 275-gallon poly tote. Allied International Emergency personnel stated that the poly tote became damaged when it came in contact with the trailer wall and was torn. Allied International Emergency personnel neutralized the impacted areas and used granular absorbents to collect the material. Allied International Emergency personnel stated that an additional fifty (50) gallons of product was captured in containment and absorbents. The spent absorbents and debris were placed into three (3) 55-gallon poly drums and was staged onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilizing. The remaining product was transferred to a new poly tote forwarded on to the consignee. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column168: On April 4, 2023, at 1700 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar Ranger personnel in Pooler, Georgia regarding the release of approximately 1 gallon of Sparclean Sanitizer 54 (Corrosive liquids, n.o.s., (contains sodium hypochlorite), UN1760, 8, III) and 1 gallon of Shineline Emulsifier (Corrosive liquids, n.o.s., (contains sodium hypochlorite), UN1760, 8, II).  The release was contained to a 5’ x 5’ area of the trailer floor.  No drains or waterways were affected by the release.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The affected cargo, released product, and all other waste generated were containerized in (1) 95-gallon poly drum, (4) 55-gallon poly drums and (1) 30-gallon poly drum.  The waste drums were then transported by contractors off site for proper disposal.

column168: At about 1300 hrs. on 4-8-2013, the WLE Mingo Yard Car Inspector heard a hissing sound coming from on top of car PROX 47110 and he was also able to smell a petroleum odor.  He notified the Mingo Yard Yardmaster who then called myself, John Vergis, Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE.  The Yardmaster told me that the car inspector was going to get into contact with the shipper since they were just a few minutes up the road.  Randy Mitchell from Tidewater Logistics, Phone number 817-602-4898,  called to tell me that they were there looking at the car and after he described where the noise was coming from, we determined that the vacuum relief valve was defective and causing pressure to leave the tank.  They had no way of mitigating the leak so I called Specialized Professional Services out of Washington, PA to come out and look at the car.  We were not able to plug the valve because it was a flanged type device.  SPSI took thick rubber gloves and covered the valve and then secured the gloves to the valve with pipe clamps. SPSI then was in communication with the car owner so that we could confirm the proper valve that needs to go back on the car.  As of the date of this report, the car is still not repaired but we are monitoring this car daily to make sure it is no longer leaking.  This car will be repaired on site and then released into transportation.
column169: Using a gas meter around the vacuum valve after loading would be beneficial.

column168: Three drums from the same shipper were discovered to be leaking when the trailer was backed up into a bay and opened. The trailer arrived at the ramp at 0129 and it was opened at around 0225. The affected packages were all at the back of the trailer. Employee who opened the trailer was immediately overwhelmed by a chemical smell. He saw liquid spilling out of the back of the trailer and several drums that were the cause. The manager on duty, was informed and took steps to move the packages to the spill cleanup area. Spill clean up specialist was informed of the spill and reported the spill To DG Admin.   The first package worked on was #516520875557. The shipper's declaration for this package was damaged and not usable. Specialist was able to read the tracking # from the stained Astra label. There was a puncture or cut in the middle of a very damaged section of the body that was flattened. It lost about half of its contents. There were no UN spec markings on the drum but as it was so badly damaged employee believe they came off. The bottom did not have any UN spec markings either. It does seem to be the same type of container as the second package which had a UN spec code.   The second drum was 516520875465. This package was going to a different recipient as the other two. This drum also had a flattened body but this had exposed a seam/weld unlike package 1. There was about 1L of liquid left in it. Employee was able to find the UN spec code on this package. The shipper's declaration was relatively undamaged and completely readable.  The last package was 516520875524. This was going to the same recipient as the 1st package. This package was actively leaking from the bottom. There was about 3L left when put it in the salvage drum. Like the 1st package it also had no UN spec code but it is believed it is the same as the second package. There was a prominent deformation near the bottom of the drum. The shipper's declaration was intact for this package.  It is reported these packages all failed as they were not properly blocked and braced. They were free to move around the trailer and eventually hit something which caused them to fail.

SequenceEvent: We were alerted to come to the end of the IC2 belt because a hazmat package had a big wet spot on the top and side. The leak contaminated all 3 bottles. DescribePack: Loose caps on all 3 bottles but only 1 leaked. The paper seal on the leaking bottle had a 1/8 inch hole/crack in the top of the seal. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: We responded quickly to the radio call of a potential hazmat leaking package. We isolated it immediately in the hazmat cage in a lined tote and place under the air vent. There were no other packages that were effected by the leaking hazmat package.

column168: On April 6, 2023, two (2) 5-gallon pails of paint (UN1263) were crushed in transit and released approximately one (1) gallon of paint to the trailer floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration (ER) to remediate the impacted surface. ER personnel placed the two (2) damaged pails in one (1) 55-gallon drum. The crew utilized granular absorbents and hand tools to collect and containerize all paint impacted material in the same 55-gallon drum for disposal.

On April 12, 2023, at 1800 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal XAB, experienced a UN3266 “FC 509 P” release from a 5-gallon poly pail due to a forklift puncture. No soil, drains, or waterways were reported to have been impacted. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct all on site cleanup activities. On April 12, 2023, at 1900 EST, Hepaco arrived on site and confirmed approximately 3-gallons of product released to a 5' x 5' area of the trailer floor and asphalt lot below due to a forklift puncture. Most of the product reportedly leaked through the trailer floor to the parking lot. The crew used a citric acid solution on the trailer floor and then deployed Oil Dri to collect the released product from both impacted areas. The damaged pail was placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. All impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were placed into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

A fiberboard box was found during sort operations at the Rochester facility with signs of release. While investigating the fiberboard box it was discovered that the cap was loose on the plastic jug inside.  The plastic jug was inside of a plastic bag and had shredded paper as dunnage. It was placed into a steel salvage package and the shipper was contacted for an amended declaration for movement.

A plastic jerrycan was found leaking in the dangerous goods building at the Memphis hub. While investigating the jerrycan the spill agent discovered a small puncture on the side. It was placed into a steel salvage package and the shipper was contacted for an amended declaration.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XSL experienced a release from a 2,111-pound UN2794 Battery, wet, filled with acid. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of product released to a 1' x 1' area of the concrete dock floor due to loose caps as well as an exposed and pinched wire. All impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column42: AEROSOLS, POISON, PACKING GROUP III (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: Package containing UN1950 Aerosols, Flammable was discovered with a stain and strong smell while loading into a ULD at our Phoenix Ramp location. After DG admin was contacted, employees were instructed to take pictures of all sides of the package, open the package, and take pictures of the inside. Upon inspection discovered a fiberboard box containing 36 cans of QD RVP Cleaner.  1 can was empty with the top of the cap cracked in half. The contents leaked within the package with yellow absorbent pads holding some of the leakage, but resulting in a stain and strong smell on the outside. After separating the broken can from the others, they decided to bag all of the good cans separately, bag the broken can with the absorbent pads, and the package itself, and place all 3 bags in a drum filled with vermiculite. An attempt was made to call the shipper to see if they would like to pick up the drum or send it on with an amended shipper's declaration. The drum will bestored awaiting further disposition.

column168: On April 3, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of methanol (UN1230) was punctured during transit and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the pallet and trailer floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted surface. PACIFIC SCIENTIFIC EMC WAS CONDUCTING OVERTIME OPERATIONS ON A FIRDAY. AT APPROXIMANTLY 0900 A VEHICLE WAS ALLOWED THRU OUR SECURITY GATE TO DELIVER A PACKAGE. THE DRIVER HANDED A PACKAGE OF EXPLOSIVE MATERIAL OFF TO OUR RECEIVING PERSON. THE ITEM WAS PLACED ON THE RECEIVING PROCESSING CART FOR PROCESSING. IT WAS SEVERAL MOMENTS LATER WHEN THE LEAD MATERIAL HANDLER (BRENNAN STENBERG) AND I (CHARLES ABEL, TRANSPORTATION OFFICER) WENT INTO THE RECEIVING AREA, THAT WE REALIZED THAT THE MATERIAL DELIVERED WAS A 1.1D MATERIAL.   OUR FACILITY WAS NOT EXPECTING THAT MATERIAL TO ARRIVE, AS IT CANNOT BE STORED IN OUR BUILDING (SHIPPING / RECEIVING), BUT MUST BE TRANSPORTED TO OUR POWDER PROCESSING AREA FOR DELIVERY. AS WE BEGAN GOING THRU THE PAPERWORK, WE NOTICED SEVERAL INCONSISTANCIES. THE VEHICLE THAT IT SHOWED DEPARTING WAS A TRACTOR-TRAILER (TRACTOR40331, TRAILER 5212 F) AND THE VEHICLE THAT IT WAS DELIVERED IN WAS A FORD TRANSIT VAN.   AFTER CONTACTING SECURITY FOR VIDEO FOOTAGE, WE NOTICED THAT THE MODEL WAS A WINDOWED (PASSENGER?) MODEL. THE VEHICLE ALSO ENTERED THE FACILITY WITH NO PLACARDS ON ANY SIDE OF THE VEHICLE.WE IMMEDIATELY FLAGGED THE VIDEO FOR RETENTION.   AFTER THIS WE REACHED OUT TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER (JET RESEARCH CENTER, HALLIBURTON) FOR VERIFICATION OF THE CONDITION IN WHICH THAT MATERIAL LEFT THEIR FACILITY. JESSICA HERNANDEZ WAS THE TRANSPORTATION CONTACT. SHE VERIFIED THAT THE VEHICLE THAT DEPARTED WITH THE MATERIAL FROM THEIR FACILITY WAS INDEED A TRACTOR-TRAILER. SHE RELAYED THE CONDITION OF THE MATERIAL ONCE IT ARRIVED TO OUR FACILITY. SHE STATED THAT SHE WOULD CONTACT HER MANAGER, AND THEY WOULD REACH OUT TO THE CARRIER.   HALLIBURTON HAS MADE SEVERAL ATTEMPTS WITH THE CARRIER TO RECEIVE INFORMATION ABOUT WHAT TRANSPIRED BETWEEN THE DEPARTURE FROM THEIR FACILITY, AND THE ARRIVAL AT OUR FACILITY. THEY (HALLIBURTON) HAVE RECEIVED NO INFORMATION BACK AT THIS TIME.  DUE TO THE 30 REPORTING REQUIREMENT, THIS REPORT WILL LACK A FULL DESCRIPTION OF THE EVENTS THAT OCCURRED AND THE REASON FOR THEM.   1.1D MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED OFF THE INSPECTED, SECURED TRUCK THAT DEPARTED HALLIBURTON IN ALVARADO, TX. IT ARRIVED ON AN UN-PLACARDED, UNSECURED PASANGER VAN TO OUR FACILITY IN CHANDLER, AZ.   NO MATERIAL WAS DISCHARGE FROM PACKAGING.  NOTHING FURTHER TO REPORT AT THIS TIME.
column169: COMPANIES MUST ENSURE THAT 49 CFR TRAINING IS COMPLETED BY ALL PERSONNEL PARTICIPATING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TRANSPORTATION AND THAT REFRESHERS ARE DONE ACCORDING TO THE PRESCRIBED TIMELINES.   DRIVES NEED TO RECIEVE TRAINING ABOUT THE RAMIFICATIONS OF VOILATIONS TO THAT CODE, INCLUDING FINES AND OTHER PENELTIES LEVIED BY THE DOT.   COMPANIES MUST ALSO ASSIST MUCH BETTER IN PROVIDING INFORMATION AFTER AN INCIDENT HAS BEEN REPORTED TO THEM, SO THAT ALL THE PROPER REPORTS CAN BE SUBMITTED IN A TIMLEY MANNER.

column42: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES PACKED WITH EQUIPMENT
column168: Courier from our station in Lancaster, PA was beginning their delivery route when it came to his attention that a package out for delivery was warm to the touch and was beginning to smoke and have thermal runaway.  Package was packed in a FedEx pak and originated in Hong Kong. It was reported the package was damaged when it arrived to the station location.  Cause of damage is unknown  The courier took the package back to the station and it was placed in a steel salvage drum.    Inspection of the package found that it contained an Infrared Thermal Camera used for inspections.  This camera was placed in a soft pouch and was not packed in a sturdy outer box.  This camera contained a 3.7V lithium  battery which would have fallen under a UN 3481 Section II and markings were not required.  Incident was called in into the NRC under report number 1364813. column168: On April 5, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum containing UN1263 was punctured during transit and released approximately two (2) gallons of product to the trailer floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services who dispatched a crew from SET Environmental (SET) to remediate the impacted surface. On April 21st DG Admin was called about a leaking package that appeared to be undeclared.  There were no markings on the outside of the package that indicated and hazardous materials were inside.  DG Admin instructed the station to open the package and there was a 1 gallon can of PPG PSX 700 that was dented  and had the top pop off and the contents leaked out.  DG Admin found a Safety Data Sheet for the same product by the same manufacturer that states it is UN3066 Paint, 8, PGIII.  The other small cans in the package had no label.  DG Admin advised the station to place the package in a salvage drum and await further disposition.

column168: On April 1, 2023, Frontier Tank Lines called ERTS to report a diesel fuel release as result of an over fuel. The Frontier Tank Lines truck was delivering fuel and didn't shut off due to a malfunction.  Lonestar Hazmat was dispatched to perform the cleanup. Lonestar arrived onsite and advised a 100ft-by-100ft area of asphalt was impacted by an estimated 100 gallons of diesel fuel. No storm drains or waterways were impacted. Lonestar applied absorbent material to the impacted asphalt. There was also a thin trail of diesel that migrated under about 18 parked tractor trailers but half of them did not have drivers on site.  There were a few additional puddles that were found that the contractor spread absorbents over. The crew used a pressure washer on the large area of the asphalt and the trail under the parked tractor trailers could not be cleaned properly at that time. Landstar would return once the trucks were moved. Four 55-gallon supersacks and one 330-gallon tote was generated and would be staged in New Braunfels TX, until proper disposal.

SequenceEvent: Operations admin were advised a fully regulated hazmat spill had occurred at the end of Hub Load Area 5, near V101 door. A work area manager was questioned about the color of the diamond label (red or black and white) to determine whether the spill consisted of a corrosive or flammable liquid and what initial PPE should be donned. Management did not know and neglected to call over the radio to determine this; WAM was advised to keep an eye on the colors of hazard diamond labels in the future as it may help to expedite admin-led spill response.     After gathering spill response equipment (including 2020 ERG), three admin and one qa manager responded to spill cleanup; began blotting liquid with absorbent pads and neutralizing spill radius. DescribePack: One plastic 5 gallon pail/bucket was observed to be the source of spillage. The cap closure was not found and it is unclear whether the cap was initially loose or broke free from rough handling of Incompatible packages. V101 door typically houses trailers intended for loading of Incompatible packages. Of the 5 gallons, 4.9 gallons were released at the time of discovery. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: At the site, management advised package handlers to vacate the area temporarily. Corrosive PPE was donned, neutralizer and absorbent pads were gathered by admin. The pail/bucket was isolated in a lined open tote to negate any closed reaction or pressure build up. The UN number was identified and the 2020 ERG was consulted for UN1760 materials to review PPE required/fire/first aid measures. Admin started systemically blotting and absorbing fluid. Neutralizer was applied to the entire area and collected once reaction had subsided. Spillage and absorbent pads were collected and transferred to the HMPA.    Once neutralization and absorption was complete, admin provided the SDS for Operations Safety personnel and the contracted custodian team with Section 4 highlighted, in case exposure symptoms were observed with any contracted vendor or employee.

column168: SequenceEvent: The package in question was loaded on the P&D vehicle that it was assigned it to. It was not placed in accordance to the way the orientation arrows on the packaging indicated. Combining that with the fact that one of the inner containers had a loose cap, it caused a leak of the hazardous material. The  material reacted with the aluminum floor of the vehicle. The reaction caused smoke to come out as well as an extremely noxious odour. The package was taken out of the building and the FXG Emergency Spill Response line was used. DescribePack: One of the 4 inner containers had a cap that was completely loose, which lead to the leak when the package was placed on its side. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: The vehicle was taken out of the building and the package was removed thereafter.

column168: SequenceEvent: Driver stated the package was loaded on the floor of the vehicle. She attempted the delivery around 11:55 AM, but she didn't remove the package from the vehicle after confirming the recipient wasn't home. By the time she arrived at her next stop she could smell an odor coming from the package compartment. She noticed it was coming from Haz Mat package and it was leaking. DescribePack: There's no clear information on what failed and how. The driver did take pictures of the leaking package. It appears that it may have been turned  on it's side or upside down prior to leaking or returned to the correct orientation. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: ERTS was contacted and a Haz Mat cleanup team was dispatched.

SequenceEvent: Driver found box leaking on delivery truck and placed it in a plastic trash bag and isolated it from other packages. Told QA about it when they returned to the station and we had to use a pry bar to get it unstuck from the floor of the truck. DescribePack: Box was completely covered in glue and leaking.  When box was cut open, 1 1gal can of Dural 452 LV 2:1 Part A and 1 1gal can of Dural 452 LV 2:1 Part B were dented and lids were loose or off.  Both cans had spilled contents into the box and on to the delivery truck and station floors.  3rd can of Part A was still closed, but glued to the box.  None of the cans had paint clips or other means of keeping the lids closed. Box was marked as a Class 8 fully regulated hazmat, but shipping label was not Hazmat service code.  Box was potentially loaded on its side due to no Hazmat service.  Box was sent on overhead belts instead of IC belts as a Hazmat. DurationRel: 5 and MitigateEffect: Driver put box into a plastic trash bag and isolated from other packages as much as possible.  Box transferred to a hazmat bin once the driver returned and we were able to pry it off the floor of the truck.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal UDV experienced a UN3266 Liquid 90 release from 55-gallon poly drums. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3-ounces of product released to the lids only of (3) 55-gallon poly drums due to loose caps. The caps were tightened, secured, and a slosh test preformed on the drums to ensure there would be no further release. The drums were wiped down and all impacted rags were placed into a 5-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-gallons of product released to a 10' x 10' area of the concrete dock floor due to a forklift puncture. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon poly overpack. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted area and then collected into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On April 20, 2023, at 1245 hours, FRA inspector reported at the CSXT Rice Yard he had discovered GATX22059, a residue tank car of Phosphoric Acid Solution leaking vapors from manway. The car was isolated and Nutrien, the shipment consignee, was notified (via CHEMTREC Report #2023-0420-00190). Hulls Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched and found 6 of 6 manway cover swing bolts less than tool tight.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to Nutrien's representative- Matt Paynter (706-564-8118). Contractor personnel also noted the manway cover gasket was not properly installed.  After ensuring proper alignment of the gasket, contractor personnel secured all 6 manway cover bolts, and the car was released for Transporation.  Note: No visible liquid was observed to have released from the tank car; however, FRA personnel advised CSX that this defect constituted a non-accident release.

column168: On April 26, 2023, at 1137 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Landstar personnel in Laredo, Texas regarding the release of approximately 3 gallons of IMP-IDAP-2010 (Flammable liquid, n.o.s., UN1993, 3, II) from (1) 275-gallon plastic tote.  The release was reportedly due to a puncture to the tote and was contained to a 8’ x 12’ area of the trailer floor.  No drains or waterways were affected by the release.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents, hand tools and the proper PPE.  All waste debris generated was containerized in (2) 55-gallon poly drums.  The waste drums were then transported offsite by contractors for proper disposal.

column168: A Superior driver had just loaded acetone onto the cargo tanker, from a rail car, at the rail spur.  The driver left the rail spur and drove the load of acetone back to the facility. When the driver stopped at the gate of the Nashville facility (518 Swinging Bridge Rd. Old Hickory, TN), acetone splashed out of the open dome lid, from compartment #1. The driver got out of the cab and noticed the dome had not been properly closed. The driver immediately realized there was a release of material and it was cleaned up by facility personnel.

column168: Package was offered to the spill agent at our Charlotte, NC ramp location emitting a strong odor.  Package was found during the offload of an aircraft during sort operations, and it appeared to be a fibreboard box containing UN 1112, Benzene.  Initially there was no indication of leakage, however further inspection found inside the outer package there was a plastic moisture barrier.  Inside this barrier were pigmats and smaller fiberboard box which did show signs of leaking.  Box contained a bottle of Benzene which was reported the cap was loose and the contents inside were leaking. Both boxes were fully marked and labeled for DG travel although shipper's declaration did not list the shipment as an overpack.  Although the contents did not breech the outer box it was seen the inner bottle was over 1/2 empty.  shipment has been placed in a steel salvage drum and is being held pending FAA investigation.

column168: GATX 6385 was found in the Rincon, NM yard with product leaking from the top of the car and down the side. Upon investigation, it was noted that the four bolts for the liquid line flange were less than tool-tight. The bolts were tool-tightened and the car was cleaned. No gasket was noted inside the liquid line cap either. The threads were taped and the cap was tool-tightened.

column168: On April 21st at approximately 8:00, a manager discovered a package with a strong odor and directed the employee to check it for being potentially undeclared DG.   The employee opened the package and it appears to be a chemical kit to repair small amounts of damage various things, including paint. The spill was completely contained within an absorbent material. Upon opening the absorbent packaging, it appears that the bottle that leaked is labeled as an activator. No liquid contaminated the rest of the box. There are no DG markings on the box nor is there a shippers declaration.  The shipment is being held pending further disposition.

column168: On April 17, 2023, twelve (12) one-gallon containers of paint were damaged by a skid steer and released approximately eight (8) gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement underneath the trailer. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Enhanced Environmental and Emergency (E3) to remediate the impacted surfaces. E3 personnel utilized granular and absorbents and hand tools to collect and containerize all paint impacted material into one (1) cubic yard bag and was staged onsite for disposal.

On April 20, 2023, four (4) one-gallon containers of UN1789 were damaged during transit and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted surface. FCE personnel deployed a neutralizing agent to the floor, followed by granular absorbents. The crew overpacked the damaged containers in one (1) 55-gallon drum. FCE then utilized hand tools to collect and containerize all UN1789 impacted absorbents in one (1) additional 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column168: A consignment (total 6 packages said to contained “musical boxes”) was reported to go into thermal runaway while in the cargo staging area inside ULD at HKG HACTL transfer warehouse. Around 1808 Z (1408 EST) an export ULD (PMC46178PO) with gross weight 3094 kg under MAWB 369-86511014 was accepted and stored in HACTL warehouse, Hong Kong  (identified as CSS compartment FR9G0755). No irregularity was observed throughout the handling and storage process of the shipper built unit. At 2022 Z (1622 EST) a fire alarm was activated. HACTL warehouse staff from the engineering and security teams arrived at the scene and found smoke from CSS compartment FR9G0755 (storage location). At 2029 Z (1629 EST) EMS (fire engines, police and ambulance arrived at scene). At 2225 Z (1825 EST) EMS Ok’d the area to be safe (fire engines, police and ambulance left the scene after confirming there was no casualty from the incident).
column169: A temporary dangerous goods embargo has been placed to the offeror/shipper until an internal investigation is completed. Cargo was set aside for inspection – unable to determine root cause at incident area. A full investigation is being conducted involving handling partners as well as HKG State authority.

On April 26, 2023, one (1) 5-gallon container of organic peroxide was damaged during transit and released approximately three (3) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted surface. FCE personnel utilized absorbents, soda ash, and hand tools to collect and containerize the damaged 5-gallon pail and all impacted debris into one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: XPO Terminal XTJ called ERTS to report a 20-gallon spill of UN1993 "ZEP BRAKE FLUSH VOC_L&K_53GL" from a 53-gallon metal drum that was caused by a dock worker clipping the drum against other freight during dock operations and impacting their dock floor near door 27. ERTS dispatched a contractor due to the volume of material released. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-gallons of product had released from the drum. When crew arrived, the terminal personnel had already patched the drum and cleaned the released product. The impacted absorbents were placed into a 55-gallon metal drum. Contractors containerized the damaged drum into an 85-gallon metal overpack. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On April 21, 2023, at 1600 ET, Circle K reported 60-gallons of diesel fuel released from tank # 563H impacting the asphalt parking lot due to a mechanical issue in the hose while delivering. On April 21, 2023, at 1958 ET, ERTS dispatched Alpha-Omega Training and Compliance (AOTC) to the site to perform all clean-up actives. Prior to AOTC arrival The fire department prevented any drains from being impacted with oil dri. Upon arrival, AOTC confirmed 60-gallons of product released impacting a 120' x 15' area of the asphalt parking lot. Absorbent pads were used to wipe up puddled areas of diesel fuel. Granular absorbent were swept into the impacted area. AOCT collected and containerized (2) 55-gallon drums of absorbent, one drum metal and one poly. All waste was transported off site for disposal.

Package arrived at our station in Reno Nevada.  It is reported the package, which was packed as an overpack, consisted of drums containing UN3082 each drum was separated by partial fibreboard boxes and shrink wrapped with black film.  Shipment was seen to have a smell of hydraulic fluid and the inner plastic and fibreboard was wet from previous legs of travel.  All drums were seen to have damage to chines and bodies, though it is not certain from where the leakage was originating.  All drums were secured in steel salvage packages and consignee was contacted for disposition.

On April 28, 2023, at 0725 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal XRC, experienced a UN1760 “Nalco EC5427A” release from a 55-gallon metal drum due to a forklift puncture. ERTS dispatched Hepaco to conduct all on site cleanup and overpacking operations. On April 28, 2023, at 1038 EST, Hepaco personnel arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5-gallons of product released to a 4’ x 6’ area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. The damaged drum was containerized into an 85-gallon poly over pack. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted area. The impacted absorbents and cleanup debris were collected and containerized into a 30-gallon poly drum. All waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 04/13/2023, at 0954 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parkersburg Yard discovered UTLX 952520, a loaded  tank car of Isoprene, Stabilized, leaking from the top of the car. Specialized Professional Services, Inc., a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the A-End liquid valve operating handle partially open and the secondary closure plug improperly installed. Contractor personnel closed A-end liquid valve operating handle, removed the secondary closure plug, and properly installed the closure in accordance with 49 CFR 173.31. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.  Cause Code: 317 NARRI: 100

column168: On 4/03/2023 Veolia employees from the Schenectady, NY ten day intransit facility were unloading drums from a trailer into another trailer when an employee noticed that a 55-gallon steel drum leaked during the initial shipment. The leak occurred in a trailer that arrived from the Veolia, Kenmore, NY 10-day transfer location. The shipment was picked up by Veolia on 3/29/2023 and then driven to the Veolia, Schenectady office on 3/31/2023 and subsequently offloaded on 4/3/23. Employees opened the trailer on 4/3/23 and observed a 55 gallon drum containing flammable liquids was slowly leaking. The drum had a dent and small hole in it. Liquid was observed beneath the drum on the floor but did not leak out of the vehicle.   The drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon salvage drum, the spill cleaned up, and transportation to the ultimate disposal facility was continued. The drum leaked about 1 gallon of a class 3 flammable liquid solution. The liquid was cleaned up with spill pads and absorbent and the lid on the drum was overpacked properly to prevent it from spilling. The duration of release is anticipated to be about 3 to 5 days and an estimated 1 gallon of flammable liquids leaked. The drum was still substantially full when the leak was discovered. No material made is outside the vehicle.
column169: On 4/03/2023 the Veolia safety manager was notified of the spill. The results of the investigation revealed the drum and small hole occurred from time it was picked up (or prior to pick up) on 3/29/23. The drum had been impacted by an object at some point. The hole was not in the area where a typical forklift strike would happen. The dent and hole were about a third of the way up the drum.  Employees are being retrained to ensure containers are inspected prior to shipping for any possible dents and leaks. Also since the origin or the damage is unknown, employees must also assure that containers are handled safely in vehicles and that nothing can impact a container while in transit.

column168: On 4/03/2023 Veolia employees from the Marlboro, MA 10 day intransit office were starting their day when they noticed a truck had a small frozen puddle beneath it. Upon inspection it was identified that material leaked out of an IBC and then out of the vehicle. The employees opened the box van and observed a cubic yard box (IBC) containing 118 gallon size inner containers of disinfectants was leaking. Frozen liquid was observed under the IBC and beneath the box van.  The spilled disinfectant was cleaned up and absorbent was placed within the IBC and transportation to the ultimate disposal facility was continued. In total, the IBC leaked about 3 gallons of a class 8 corrosive liquid disinfectant solution. The duration of release is anticipated to be about 48 hours and an estimated 3 gallons of disinfectant leaked.
column169: On 4/03/2023 the Veolia safety manager was notified of the spill and performed an investigation. The results of the investigation is the inner containers in the IBC were not packaged correctly and did not have sufficient absorbent around them. Freezing temperatures caused inner glass bottles to break while the box van was parked for the weekend. The liner in the IBC also failed. Employees were retrained to ensure containers are packaged correctly and inspected prior to shipping. If employees are not sure of packing materials, they have been instructed to stop work and ask for assistance.

Initially believed to be just an odor, the offending packages were located inside the AKE, and were inspected for physical leaks. Both packages were from the same shipment and packaged as overpacks. No physical leakage was found.  Upon transferring both packages into salvage drums, it was seen there was an actual spill coming from one of the drums causing the odor for both.  Packages consisted of metal drums placed in plastic moisture barriers and in turn packed in an outer fibreboard box overpack.  It was not reported how or why the drum was leaking. The other package was determined to have no leak and no odor. packages were placed in steel salvage drums and shipper was contacted for am amended shipper's declaration for continued travel.

column168: As dockworker was loading the second of two totes into trailer T53165, the tote began to massively leak. The forklift could not get grip to back out of the trailer so it was towed out with another forklift. The long forks were used to pull the Ieaking tote out of the trailer. By this time most of the contents had already emptied from the trailer. The spill which began Ieaking from the trailer onto the apron/yard was walled off with absorbant to prevent spreading and continuously added as it spread. After the tote was pulled from the trailer, we could find no physical damage to it. The valve was found on the trailer floor beside where the tote was. It appears no locking seal was used on the valve. For cleanup, ACT Environmental was called. They are currently working on transferring into recovery drums.

column168: Our driver was driving in heavy stop and go traffic due to coming up on an accident. The driver in front of ours, also a tractor trailer, came to a sudden stop and our driver did not have time to stop before rear ending the trailer in front of them. Both drivers pulled off to the side to assess damage and swap information when our driver noticed some liquid seeping from out of the side of the trailer. The driver called the safety manager who contacted a spill clean up crew to the scene. In the meantime, the fire department and police department handled the scene and containing the minor spill. Once the crew arrived, it was determined that a group of 55 gallon drums were pushed to the nose of the trailer due to the harsh stop when rear ending the trailer in front of our driver. Multiple barrels were disformed, one was cracked near the top of the barrel and seeping the formaldehyde liquid onto the floor of the trailer and seeping through the crack of the trailer floor and wall onto the pavement for roughly three hours. By the time the barrel was sealed back up, 10 gallons were lost from the barrel, however less made its way through the crack of the trailer floor and onto pavement. Once the scene, cargo, and trailer were contained, our driver was able to proceed to the.next truck stop which was 4 miles away from the scene. We then took the trailer to the clean up crew's warehouse and they unloaded the trailer, decontaminated it, and reloaded the trailer.
column169: Some reccomendations beyond the individual company to improve hazardous materials transportation: - officers watching speed and space management, especially for a placarded load - more focus on speed and space management for the hazmat endorcement test

column168: Truck and tanker load were in route to destination. Driver was making a right turn at an intersection and in the process let the rear trailer tandems on the right side drop off of the pavement. This caused the truck and tanker to roll over onto its right side off of the right side of the road. When the tanker rolled over there was a minor leak of product that was dripping from the washout cap on the tanker. There was an estimated 4 gallons that leaked out and most of the product was captured in a container. There was also a small amount of engine oil and diesel from the truck that leaked out. The police, fire department responded to the scene. An emergency response contractor was also activated to respond to the scene for load transfer and cleanup and remediation. The load was successfully transferred from the damaged tanker to another tanker and transported to the destination facility. The ground was properly cleaned up and remediated.

column168: On 4/10/2023, CRDX 14235 was loaded with 200,500 lbs. of ammonium nitrate prill (AN). On 4/12/2023 the rail car departed the Dyno Nobel plant. The rail car was transported by the Union Pacific Railroad (UP) from Cheyenne to Saltdale, CA and made 19 stops over a 13-day journey, arriving on 4/25/2023.   While unloading the rail car, Saltdale employees discovered the center hopper was empty.  All seals were in place and unbroken.  Employees did not observe whether the bottom gate was completely closed before opening it.     On 5/11/2023, the loss was brought to the attention of Chuck Moody (Cheyenne Facilities Manager), who reported it to the National Response Center.   It appears that  an overspeed impact event while the rail car was being transported by UP caused the bottom center gate to open enough to leak the AN while in transit.  Dyno Nobel verified the car was not leaking before moving from the plant to the UP railyard in Cheyenne. On 4/12/2023, a Dyno Nobel employee also confirmed the CRDX 14235 was not leaking at the UP railyard.   Dyno Nobel inspected the loading site, interviewed the railcar loaders and track crew, and reviewed the loading procedures with those employees. Dyno Nobel also spoke to UP and the company maintaining the rail siding in Saltdale.  There are no reports or signs of any accumulation of AN at any stations or stops along the route.  Upon return to Cheyenne, the UP and FRA conducted an inspection of CRDX 14235 and found that a draft gear on a shock absorber was worn, which would prevent the rail car from absorbing energy associated with impacts in transit.  See attached documents for the railcar inspection report, the shipping papers, and the waybill.
column169: Dyno Nobel a is conducting a root cause analysis and having an independent inspection of the rail car.  Dyno Nobel will review the loading and unloading procedures to seek areas for improvement.  Dyno Nobel will also red tag and inspect all rail cars in its fleet with similar gate locking mechanisms.

column168: Delta received notification on 04/22/23 where a passengers SmartBag began to smoke during taxi from MCO-DTW on DL1747. After pushback, the flight crew received an aft cargo fire indication. The flight crew stopped the engine start, referenced the quick reference handbook(QRH) procedure, activated the aft cargo fire suppression system, and contacted the ramp controller to request ARFF. At that time, the flight attendants contacted the flight crew to report a burning odor and haze in the cabin. The flight crew noted that the fire indication extinguished within two minutes. The flight crew then shut down the engines and coordinated a return to the gate. After returning to the gate, the passengers deplaned. An inspection of the cargo identified a damaged passenger bag that was equipped with a battery. Maintenance personnel inspected the aircraft and replaced the recirculation, filters, the fire extinguisher bottles, as well as the regulator and dry filter.
column169: This event remains under investigation. Immediate Actions: -Notified the National Response Center(NRC) -The MCO team distributed a safety bulletin specific to smart bags- identification, battery risk and removal. -DG Safety Alert All-Division publication, emphasizing the notification procedures and identifying Smart Bag triggers -Adding additional guidance in the above wing policy(KM) for front-line agents(ECD for publication is May 15). -Coordinating with Delta's digital teams to add a summer readiness notification to customers on Delta.com regarding lithium battery safety(ECD for publication is May 15).

column168: Delta received notification on 05/01/23 of an undeclared event where two actuators(MPN 5262100; UN0276) were shipped on air waybill#73129173 from ATL Hangar Logistics to UU< on DL500 on April 27,2023. Preliminary results of the investigation revealed that the affected actuators were robbed by Hangar Maintenance in error and were placed aside for processing to remain in ATL. The following day, a Hangar employee noticed the two actuators that were removed in error, and after confirming with the Material Planners that the parts were still needed(aircraft in LAX), the employee shipped the parts undeclared utilizing a manual procedure (Handling Unit(HU) process). The event is under investigation to determine root cause and subsequent corrective actions. See the attached pictures.
column169: This event remains under investigation. The team is in the process of analyzing this event from both a local and system vantage point to determine root cause(s) and subsequent corrective actions. Comprehensive system corrective actions are will be futher developed upon root cause determination. Preliminary Actions to Prevent Recurrence: - Service Recovery executing a stand down with all team members to cover the rob process and the paperwork needed for robs and shop orders., Comprehensive Actions: - TechOps will order signage regarding process/paperwork(process) for robs and requirements to check the Dangerous Goods status for ATG, MSP and Sites - Techops training creating OJT sign-offs to allow team members to support robs, shop orders and other process steps(must be signed off to work critical areas) - Requesting enhancements to the SAP HU(manual) process to alert that the part is a stock item(submitted 5/2/23)

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Missing Component or Device
column168: At 10:00 on 4/26/2023, Kansas City Southern Railway(KCS) employees working on the mainline south of Kansas City, MO reported that the control panel on loaded tank car IAPX 1102 was frosted over and dripping. The car was set out at the KCS rail yard in Kansas City, MO. The Hazmat Department mobilized a rail qualified response contractor to investigate and mltigate the release. Upon arrival, responders determined that both L and R side cabinets were Ieaking, and began their response by attending to the L side cabinet. Responders opened the cabinet and determined that product was Ieaking from the liquid sample valve. The valve was found to be opened 1/3-1/2 turn, with no secondary closure applied to the end of the line. The valve was securely closed to stop the leak. The secondary closure plug was not found in the cabinet, so a 1/4" flared cap supplied by the responders was installed tool tight to achieve a secure secondary closure. Responders then moved to the R side cabinet, and after opening it, found that product was again Ieaking from the liquid sample valve, which was open around 1/4 turn with no secondary closure plug applied. The valve was securely closed to stop the leak. Responders located the secondary closure plug inside the cabinet, and applied it tool tight. After both leaks were stopped, zip ties were reapplied to the valve handles, and the cabinets resealed. Estimated total release is 300 gallons. Once secure,the car was then released back into transportation. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column169: several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases(a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.(Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar. com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: Rust and Sons driver entered New Mexico on eastbound I-40 near Gallup at 8:00 pm on April 11,2023. Upon entering scale area the driver was instructed to move to an inspection area to complete a Level 1 inspection. During the inspection an officer noted a strong odor coming from the trailer. The doors of the trailer were opened to reveal the odor and a suspicion that there was a material leak within the load. This was deemed a non-emergency event and the driver was instructed to detach the trail6r from the truck in a cordened off area as no leak was visible inside or outside of the trailer. On April 12, 2023 US Ecology was contacted to mobilize a team to inspect the load. Prior to their arrival a fire engine was on site conducting tests to determine if it was safe to enter the trailer. US Ecology arrived on scene around 4:00 pm that afternoon to determine the origin of the smell. No leak was discovered but the totes had vented due to bulging of the totes. The crew opened the caps and vented all totes on the trailer. This caused condensation on the top of the totes which was cleaned up and the used cleaning materials were put into a 55 gallon drum and added to the load. A manifest for this drum was created to accompany the load which was then re-directed to Rineco in Benton Ark. for final disposal. ,

A load shift punctured a tote near the top. The release was properly managed by an emergency response contractor. The contents of the tote were transferred to a new tote and held pending disposition from the shipper.

On April 14, 2023, at 1450 ET, Emergency Response and Training Solutions (ERTS) was contacted by Roadrunner Transportation personnel in Livermore, California regarding the release of approximately 12 gallons of Condensafe 230 (Corrosive liquid, n.o.s. (Sulfuric Acid), UN1760, 8, III) from (1) 55-gallon poly drum.  The release was contained to an 8’ x 2’ area of the trailer floor and continuing to a 25’ x 8’ area of asphalt beneath the trailer and was reportedly due to a load shift in transit.  No drains or waterways were affected by the release.  Contractors were dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged drum was containerized in (1) 95-gallon poly drum.  The remaining impacted material and waste debris generated were containerized in (1) 95-gallon poly drum and (2) 55-gallon poly drums.  The waste drums were then staged onsite by contractors for proper disposal.

Employee was transferring chemical from cargo tank to customer storage tank via air-offloading using approximately 10 PSI. A few minutes into transfer, employee thought that product was not flowing as it should and began trouble shooting the unloading system. While doing so, employee failed to bleed the pressure from chemical hose prior to disconnecting hose resulting in spill and chemical exposure to employee's lower face, mouth, tongue and left ear. Employee utilized on site safety shower and was later transported to local hospital for evaluation and treatment. Employee was later admitted  for observation only.
column169: Employee failed to follow established policy and procedure. Employee failed to wear proper personal protective equipment as issued and required for type of chemical being handled.  Employee to be retrained on policy and procedure. Customer unloading procedures to be reviewed with employee prior to performing live chemical transfer on site.

column168: During flight customer had battery charger plugged into laptop. After 15-20 minutes of use it began hissing and Ieaking. Customer took it back to the Flight Attendants who noticed that the batteries were also bubbling at the negative terminals. Flight Attendants placed the device in the fire containment bag. There was no fire or fumes. Customer had placed AA Duracell Alkaline batteries into USB Charger which is designed to recharge batteries such as lithium ion. The voltage/amperage mismatch between the Alkaline batteries and the laptop caused the alkalines to short and overheat. There was not thermal runaway.
